# Shared Memory

This project stores persistent memory at `agent-docs/memory/MEMORY.md` (in the repo).
The Cursor project memory (`~/.cursor/projects/<project-id>/memory/`) is symlinked to that directory — all agents (Cursor, Claude Code, etc.) read and write the same files.

When the symlink is missing or broken, create it:
```bash
ln -s <workspace>/agent-docs/memory ~/.cursor/projects/<project-id>/memory
```

## Tree structure

Memory is organized as a **tree**. Agents load only the branches relevant to their current task.

```
agent_docs/memory/
  MEMORY.md              ← root index — always loaded, max ~200 lines
  <area>.md              ← one file per functional area (branch node)
  <area>/<subtopic>.md   ← deep detail for a sub-area (leaf node)
```

### Reading the tree

1. `MEMORY.md` is always loaded automatically. It is a concise index only — no deep detail.
2. At session start, identify which area(s) your task touches from the index entries.
3. Read the relevant area file(s) before starting work.
4. If the area file links to a sub-topic file needed for your task, read that too.
5. Do not read branches unrelated to your task — keep context lean.

### Writing to the tree

- **MEMORY.md**: one-line entry per area, with a relative link to the area file. Keep it under 200 lines.
- **Area file** (`<area>.md`): all stable facts, decisions, gotchas, and patterns for that area.
- **Sub-topic file** (`<area>/<subtopic>.md`): created only when an area file grows beyond ~150 lines or a sub-topic needs isolated detail.
- When adding a sub-topic file, replace the inline detail in the area file with a one-line link.

### Example index entry in MEMORY.md

```markdown
## OCR Pipeline
Paperwork intake, zip upload, review queue, credential resolution.
→ [ocr.md](ocr.md)
```

### Example area file structure

```markdown
# OCR Pipeline

## Architecture
...

## Credentials
...
→ [credentials.md](credentials/credentials.md)  ← only if detail warrants a sub-file

## Gotchas
...
```

## When to update

Update the tree when you learn:
- A new architectural decision or pattern
- A critical "gotcha" (DB state, build requirement, PATH issue, etc.)
- A customer-facing fact that changed (business_id, credentials location, deployment state)
- A lesson from a mistake that should not be repeated

Do NOT save: in-progress task state, speculative plans, or anything already in git history.

## Format

Lead with the fact. For feedback/lessons: add a **Why:** line and a **How to apply:** line so future agents understand the context, not just the rule.
